Starting A New Django Project

create a folder(Bank)
install a virtual environment("pip install virtualenv")
assign a name to the virtual environment for example-venv ("virtualenv venv")
activate the virtual environment - for windows ("scripts\activate\venv)
				  - for linux ("source venv/bin/activate")
install django("pip install django")
to see all django command("django-admin")
create or start a project for example-studybud ("django-admin startproject studybud")
test to see if you've been sucessful all this while - for windows ("python manage.py runserver")
						      - for linux ("python3 manage.py runserver")
put in your browsers url address ("http://127.0.0.1:8000/")

open your folder(stuybud) directory in your code editor preferrably visual studio code
create an app for  example-base  - for windows ("python manage.py startapp base")
		    		     - for linux ("python3 manage.py startapp base")
go to your newly created app(base), locate your views.py file
make an import ("from django.http import HttpResponse")
still in the views.py file create a function and pass in an argument of request ("
def myFunction(request):
    return HttpResponse("My First Django Page")    
")
go to your newly created app(base), create a new file in the app directory called ("urls.py")
in the newly created file(urls.py), type in ("
from django.urls import path
from . import views
")
still in urls.py file, create a list and assign it to a variable name called urlpatterns and put in the path to your views function ("
urlpatterns = [
    path('studybud/', views.myFunction, name = 'myFunction')
]
")
now go to your project's folder(studybud), locate the urls.py file there and add include to our imports there ("
from django.urls import path, include")
add a new path to the urlpatterns dict. ("path('', include('base.urls')),") 


refresh your browser and you should see ("My First Django Page") displayed on your screen


create a folder in your app(base) called ("templates")
then create a folder in the templates folder called ("base")
create an html file and call it anything -for example(index.html)
make any design of your choice
go to your project(studybud), go your "settings.py" file, locate "INSTALLED_APPS"
add the name of your app in quotes ("
INSTALLED_APPS = [
    'django.contrib.admin',
    'django.contrib.auth',
    'django.contrib.contenttypes',
    'django.contrib.sessions',
    'django.contrib.messages',
    'django.contrib.staticfiles',

    'base',
]
")

OR

INSTALLED_APPS = [
    'django.contrib.admin',
    'django.contrib.auth',
    'django.contrib.contenttypes',
    'django.contrib.sessions',
    'django.contrib.messages',
    'django.contrib.staticfiles',

    'base.apps.BaseConfig',
]

OR

TEMPLATES = [
    {
        'BACKEND': 'django.template.backends.django.DjangoTemplates',
        'DIRS': [
            BASE_DIR / 'templates'
        ],
        'APP_DIRS': True,
        'OPTIONS': {
            'context_processors': [
                'django.template.context_processors.debug',
                'django.template.context_processors.request',
                'django.contrib.auth.context_processors.auth',
                'django.contrib.messages.context_processors.messages',
            ],
        },
    },
]


go to your views.py in your app 
you can choose to create a new function or use the initially created function
remove the ("return HttpResponse("My First Django Page")")
and replace with return render(HttpResponse, 'myfirst.html') -----("
def myFunction(request):
    return render(HttpResponse, 'myfirst.html')
")

OR

go to your views.py in your app 
you can choose to create a new function or use the initially created function
import loader from django.template ("from django.template import loader")
migrate - for windows ("python manage.py migrate")
	- for linux ("python3 manage.py migrate")
remove the ("return HttpResponse("My First Django Page")")
and replace with ("
def myFunction(request):
    template = loader.get_template('myfirst.html')
    return HttpResponse(template.render())
")


then refresh your browser and you should see your html designs displayed



Creating And Linking Static Files
STATIC_URL = 'static/'
STATICFILES_DIRS = [
    os.path.join(BASE_DIR / 'static')
]



